				<h1>15 Novels You Need to Read This Fall</h1>
		<h2>Recommendations from Your Friendly Lit Hub Editors</h2>
    <div class="inner">
		<div class="post_header_wrapper">
    				</div>
				<div class="author_info" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
			<div class="author_name">By&nbsp;<a href="https://lithub.com/author/emily-temple/" itemprop="url"><span itemprop="name">Emily&nbsp;Temple</span></a></div>
			<div class="author_hr"><hr/></div>
			<div class="publish_date">September 8, 2025</div>
		</div>
		<div class="social_links">
						<a href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?via=lithub&text=15+Novels+You+Need+to+Read+This+Fall&url=https%3A%2F%2Flithub.com%2F15-novels-you-need-to-read-this-fall%2F"><span class="social_twitter"></span></a>
			<a href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Flithub.com%2F15-novels-you-need-to-read-this-fall%2F&t=15+Novels+You+Need+to+Read+This+Fall"><span class="social_facebook"></span></a>
					</div>
    <div class="inner">
    	<!-- Begin main content -->
    	<div class="inner_wrapper fullwidth">
    			
										<!-- Begin each blog post -->
						<div class="post_wrapper" style="padding-top:0;">
							<div class="post_inner_wrapper">
						    	<div class="post_wrapper_inner">
										<div class="inner_wrapper fullwidth">
								        
										<p>The weather is changing (well, sort of), the pumpkin spice lattes are beckoning, the kids are back in school, all of which clearly indicates that it&#8217;s big book season yet again. And hey, we might not be able to read fast enough to outrun the reality of 2025, but we can try. Here are some of the new fall novels the Lit Hub editors have been reading and loving so far this year.</p>
<h2><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780802166470" class="external" target="_blank"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259219" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/15-novels-you-need-to-read-this-fall/rabih-5/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/rabih.jpg" data-orig-size="800,447" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="rabih" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/rabih-300x168.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/rabih.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-259219 size-full" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/rabih.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="447" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/rabih.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/rabih-300x168.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/rabih-768x429.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/rabih-60x34.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/rabih-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></h2>
<h2><strong>Rabih Alameddine, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780802166470" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The True True Story of Raja the Gullible (and His Mother)</a></em><br />
Grove Press, September 2</strong></h2>
<p>This decades-spanning seventh novel from the National Book Award finalist and PEN/Faulkner Award-winning author ofÂ <em>An Unnecessary Woman</em>Â andÂ <em>The Angel of History</em>Â is a wondrously exuberant, fearlessly political mother-son saga set against the roiling backdrop of some of the most traumatic events in Beirutâ€™s recent history: the Lebanese Civil War, the 2019 economic collapse, the Covid-19 pandemic, and the 2020 port explosion.</p>
<p>The caustic-but-compassionate Raja is a 63-year-old gay Beiruti high school teacher who, due to the characteristically selfish behavior of his princeling older brother, finds himself once again sharing a living space with hisÂ mouthy firebrand of a mother (a magnificent creation). An invitation to an all-expenses-paid writing fellowship in Virginia (extended to Raja even though he hasnâ€™t put pen to paper in twenty-five years), sends our protagonist down an anarchic, era-jumping rabbit warren of memory.</p>
<p>I can think of few novelists more skilled in the art of blending deep trauma with irreverent humor than Rabih Alameddine. Youâ€™re so damn charmed by the irascible charisma of his narratorsâ€”by their wicked bite and breezy self-deprecation and gimlet eyesâ€”that youâ€™ll let them ferry you to the most heartbreaking and harrowing of places.Â <em>Raja the Gullible</em> is another tragicomic triumph. <em>â€“Dan Sheehan, Book Marks Editor-in-Chief</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593835173" class="external" target="_blank"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259220" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/15-novels-you-need-to-read-this-fall/middlespoon/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/middlespoon.jpg" data-orig-size="800,447" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="middlespoon" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/middlespoon-300x168.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/middlespoon.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-259220" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/middlespoon.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="447" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/middlespoon.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/middlespoon-300x168.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/middlespoon-768x429.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/middlespoon-60x34.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/middlespoon-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>
<h2><strong>Alejandro Varela, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593835173" class="external" target="_blank">Middle Spoon</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>Viking, September 9</strong></h2>
<p>This novel is a spiral, carrying readers down, down, down into the uncomfortable depths of heartbreak. Our narrator, a gay, happily married father of two disentangling himself from a poly love affair, isâ€”depending on the lightâ€”brilliant, self-mythologizing, abject, hopeful, and vulnerable. I love Varela&#8217;s style, which manages to capture <em>a certain guy</em> (read: hand-wringing, over-educated, PMC elder Millennial flirting with socialism) in a light more precise and endearing than certain snider peers have chosen. But I love even better the <em>ideas</em> this book takes seriously.</p>
<p>Open relationships, medical inequality, and electoral socialism aren&#8217;t engaged as jokes or mere biographical shorthand here. Our protagonist feels, lives, and thinks through his ethical dilemmas in the macro-world even as he flops around tortured in the mini-one, trying to throw back his unwanted hurt person thoughts like they&#8217;re so much extraneous fish. I&#8217;d give this novel to anyone going through a sea change in lifestyle. Our unnamed hero&#8217;s one-sided correspondence is exhausting, familiar, humiliating, and rewarding all at once. Just like that new kind of love he&#8217;s attempting. A very human and painfully contemporary project. <em>â€“Brittany Allen, Staff Writer</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781566897358" class="external" target="_blank"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259221" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/15-novels-you-need-to-read-this-fall/helen-2/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/helen.jpg" data-orig-size="800,447" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="helen" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/helen-300x168.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/helen.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-259221 size-full" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/helen.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="447" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/helen.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/helen-300x168.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/helen-768x429.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/helen-60x34.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/helen-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>
<h2><strong>Makenna Goodman, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781566897358" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Helen of Nowhere</a></em><br />
Coffee House Press, September 9</strong></h2>
<p>As a lapsed Classics major, Makenna Goodman&#8217;s sophomore novel had me at the title, but this slim, sly novel had much more to offer than mythology-bait. The novel concerns a disgraced former professor (the Man) and his mannered raging against women (one in particular, but really, of course, all women), looking at real estate after the Fall. The novel&#8217;s formal experiments (realtor-as-oracle) are grounded by a sharp humor. Despite its length, <em>Helen of NowhereÂ </em>manages to feel epic in the best wayâ€”the characters feel both familiar and new, the folly of Man is on full display, and on a sentence level, it&#8217;s the kind of book that forces you to underline. Goodman&#8217;s novel is a tribute to her influences, and a crackling joy to read.Â  <em>â€“Jessie Gaynor, Senior Editor</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593718551" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259222" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/15-novels-you-need-to-read-this-fall/lockwood-3/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/lockwood.jpg" data-orig-size="800,447" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="lockwood" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/lockwood-300x168.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/lockwood.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-259222 size-full" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/lockwood.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="447" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/lockwood.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/lockwood-300x168.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/lockwood-768x429.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/lockwood-60x34.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/lockwood-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>
<h2><strong>Patricia Lockwood, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593718551" class="external" target="_blank">Will There Ever Be Another You</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>Riverhead, September 23</strong></h2>
<p>Oh, Trish. If every generation gets the saint they deserve, you are cause to hope. All hail this ardent, ferocious, baroque, bonkers bard. If you know you know, and won&#8217;t need convincing. But everyone else? Time to join or die.</p>
<p>Lockwood, who&#8217;s been erroneously pegged as an internet bard while managing to craft a literary project that is much bigger than anything Zuckerberg hath wrought, has a new gift for us. Her latest novel continues a confident structural weirding first attempted in her last book,<em> <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593189597" class="external" target="_blank">No One is Talking About This.</a></em> But this novel has even less narrative. It&#8217;s more an act of decoupage. Told in poetic, dazzling, and sometimes elliptical vignettes, <em>There Will Never Be Another You</em> begins with illness in Ireland and leapfrogs, like the chronically scattered mind it takes as subject, over many disaggregated memories. Our narrator (presumably Trish) is a victim of Long Covid, and as she works to reconstruct her foggy mind we in the cheap seats are treated to a close read of <em>Anna Karenina</em>, collaboration chronicles starring the playwright Heidi Schreck and a doomed television adaptation, and many vivid &#8220;visuals&#8221; care of a hallucinogenic mushroom tea. The prose is ecstatic and freaky and muscular. But this is a book that resists binging. As with all her other offerings, there&#8217;s gold among the grit. <em>â€“BA</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811238830" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259223" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/15-novels-you-need-to-read-this-fall/ravn-2/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/ravn.jpg" data-orig-size="800,447" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="ravn" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/ravn-300x168.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/ravn.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-259223" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/ravn.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="447" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/ravn.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/ravn-300x168.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/ravn-768x429.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/ravn-60x34.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/ravn-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>
<h2><strong>Olga Ravn, tr. Martin Aitken, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811238830" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Wax Child</em></a><br />
New Directions, September 30</strong></h2>
<p>Fans of Olga Ravnâ€™s beautiful and weird stories no doubt have this one on their list already, and it very much lives up to the hype. <em>The Wax Child</em> is an eerie, unsettling book about a group of women who have apparently been possessed and empowered by a tall and headless Devil. A trial and imprisonment ensues.</p>
<p>But this isn&#8217;t a typical, seventeenth century witch trial story.Â For one it&#8217;s is narrated by a handmade doll, with strange and roaming powers of observation. Ravnâ€™s prose is striking too, richly marbled with quotation and detail pulled from primary source letters and court documents. The texture of this true language of spells and grimoires is engrossing, and perfect alongside Ravnâ€™s keen ear for viscera: blood sucked from a cut finger, pens scratching and leaking,Â teeth sliding through the narrator&#8217;s wax body.</p>
<p>What might otherwise be a straightforward creepy historical novel is deepened by these uncanny phrasings, and Ravn&#8217;s attention to the social bonds in this world.Â <em>The Wax Child</em> is about the dread of living in brutal hierarchies, and the shapes that friendship and protection take to counteract these grim realities. I was particularly moved by the portrayals of community, especially the sequences of shared work. Ties built through crafting and cooking are constructed out of something other than blood, either shared or drawn. Ravn beautifully brings us inside these circles of care, which to many outsiders might have seemed as strange as witchery. <em>â€“James Folta, Staff Writer</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780802165176" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259209" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/15-novels-you-need-to-read-this-fall/heartthelover-copy2/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/heartthelover-copy2.jpg" data-orig-size="800,447" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="heartthelover copy2" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/heartthelover-copy2-300x168.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/heartthelover-copy2.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-259209 size-full" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/heartthelover-copy2.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="447" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/heartthelover-copy2.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/heartthelover-copy2-300x168.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/heartthelover-copy2-768x429.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/heartthelover-copy2-60x34.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/heartthelover-copy2-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>
<h2><strong>Lily King,Â <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780802165176" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Heart the Lover</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Grove Press, September 30</strong></h2>
<p>Hereâ€™s something about me: I donâ€™t really like books that try too hard to make me feel things. I never â€œget the tissues ready.â€ I donâ€™t go in for â€œheartbreaking.â€ Lily King, though, is some kind of genius, because in a scant 250 pages, this book both delighted me intellectually and affected me on a profound emotional plane. Or several planes, because this book, short as it is, manages to be many things at once.</p>
<p><i>Heart the Lover </i>is a campus novel that feels as pleasurable and nostalgic as <i>The Secret History </i>(without the murder). Itâ€™s a book about being a young person and a book about not being young anymore. Itâ€™s a book about love and regret and the relentless passage of time. Itâ€™s a book about other books. Itâ€™s both a prequel and a sequel to Kingâ€™s 2020 novel <i>Writers &amp; Lovers</i>, a book I liked so much that at the time, I <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hub-recommends-writers-lovers-reply-all-and-the-marvelous-mrs-maisel/">bemoaned it</a> for not being long enough. (Thank you for answering my plea, Lily.) Itâ€™s the best love story Iâ€™ve read all year, and the day I finished reading it, I did something I have never done before: I put my copy into an envelope and sent it to my best friend, so that I&#8217;d have someone to talk to about it. Yuck, feelings! But somehow I&#8217;m not even that mad about it. <em>â€“Emily Temple, Managing Editor</em></p>
