<h2><strong>Grace Byron, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668087862" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Herculine</a><br />
</em>S&amp;S/Saga Press, October 7</strong></h2>
<p>This debut is for the queer girlies with religious trauma (which is to say, all of my friends). <em>Herculine</em> follows a young trans woman who decides to fight her malaiseâ€”and her demonic visionsâ€”by joining her exâ€™s trans girl commune in rural Indiana. What could go wrong! Byronâ€™s novel is dark and voicey and funny in a way that makes you feel like youâ€™re talking to a cool friend who youâ€™re secretly worried about. Like if your coolest, most unstable friend decided to open up to you about the literal demons that have been following her around but you thought you guys were just gonna grab coffee and catch up about boyfriend drama. You know the vibe. I always love when a novel captures a voice so clearly, and I love a novel thatâ€™s creepy and spooky, and this book delivers on all of that. Plus, the cover! Come on. Your sleep paralysis demon is begging you to read <em>Herculine</em>. <em>â€“McKayla Coyle, Publishing Coordinator</em></p>
