<p>Costaâ€™s debut novel is a little bit Steinbeck in Washington, a little bit <em>As I Lay Dying</em> in the Olympic peninsula, a little bit Annie Proulx in the Pacific northwest. <em>The Great Work</em> is about a grizzled alchemist and his nephew tracking a strange creature through the Washington wilderness near the end of the nineteenth century. Itâ€™s dark and moody, but also grounded and human. Thereâ€™s a very classic sensibility to the novel, by which I mean itâ€™s kind of about everything in the way that the great novels of yore tended to be. But not in an annoying way! In a way that feels so genuine and satisfying that I know itâ€™s going to settle into a corner of my mind and live there forever. Costa has fashioned a world that you canâ€™t help but be sucked into; the kind of world that feels so full and visceral that youâ€™ll find yourself lost in it for hours. I loved this weird, muddy, beautiful book. <em>â€“MC</em></p>
<p><a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063439948" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259257" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/15-novels-you-need-to-read-this-fall/helm/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/helm.jpg" data-orig-size="800,447" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="helm" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/helm-300x168.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/helm.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-259257 size-full" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/helm.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="447" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/helm.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/helm-300x168.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/helm-768x429.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/helm-60x34.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/helm-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>
<h2><strong>Sarah Hall, </strong><a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063439948" class="external" target="_blank"><strong><em>Helm</em></strong></a><br />
<strong>Mariner, November 4</strong></h2>
<p>I love the weather. I love thinking about the weather, I love watching the weather, I love the ways that human beings have interacted with and personified and generally related to the weather. <em>Helm</em> is about the only named wind in the British isles and by taking on Helm as a through-line slash main-character, Hall produces a stirring, funny, absolutely idiosyncratic history-novel. Itâ€™s also an urgently-felt climate novel, becauseâ€”spoilers, I guess, unless youâ€™ve looked outside for even a moment in the last several yearsâ€”climate change threatens not only Helm but the delicate balance of which Helm is only one piece. There are predecessors to this novelâ€”George R. Stewartâ€™s <em>Storm</em> certainly comes to mind â€” but this is a perfect meeting of mind, style, moment, and story. If one of the major ethical questions of our time, per Robert Macfarlane, asks â€œis a river alive?,â€ Sarah Hall convincingly argues that the wind certainly is. <em>â€“DB</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593731918" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259258" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/15-novels-you-need-to-read-this-fall/findhim/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/findhim.jpg" data-orig-size="800,447" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="findhim" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/findhim-300x168.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/findhim.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-259258 size-full" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/findhim.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="447" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/findhim.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/findhim-300x168.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/findhim-768x429.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/findhim-60x34.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/findhim-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>
<h2><strong>Elaine Kraf, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593731918" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Find Him!</a><br />
</em>Modern Library, November 11</strong></h2>
<p>Iâ€™ve said it previously on the Lit Hub podcast, but weâ€™re overdue for a Elaine Krafaissance. Her work was ahead of the curve, and her novels are more accessible than ever thanks to Modern Libraryâ€™s reissues, complete with excellent new introductions. Iâ€™ve yet to read a dud from Kraf, but <em>Find Him!</em>Â is a great place to start, a strange and engaging 1977 mystery that blends fantastical dreaming, pervasive nightmare, and patriarchal oppression.</p>
<p>This book is a stylish pastiche, as an unnamed woman fitfully reconstructs herself under the thumb of a strange man. <em>Find Him!</em>â€™s narrator regains consciousness dressed in a school uniform, in a place she doesnâ€™t recognize, and without the ability to speak. She canâ€™t do anythingâ€”speak, eat, batheâ€”without the help of a man named Oliver. Terrifyingly, he seems to play every role in her life: father, lover, guide, torturer. His wife has vanished (huh!), and he seems to be pouring all of his energies into the care and keeping of this mystery woman, who he explains is an alien, arrived from another star.</p>
<p>The woman is able to escape, in a way, and steps out into society. This is where the book really shines: seeing the world through her eyes, and watching her unravel her relationship with Oliver, is exhilarating, especially as told through Krafâ€™s excellent prose and fascinating formal experimentation.</p>
<p>The novelÂ digs at one of Krafâ€™s thematic obsessions: characters who are outside of the norm, and the ways that others try to trap them. Who are we within society&#8217;s confines? The answers to troubling questions often arrive sideways in <em>Find Him!</em>, and in strange form. Alongside all of Krafâ€™s work, <em>Find Him!</em> feels destined to take a significant place in feminist literature. <em>â€“JF</em></p>
<p><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374618315" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259259" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/15-novels-you-need-to-read-this-fall/laing/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/laing.jpg" data-orig-size="800,447" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="laing" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/laing-300x168.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/laing.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-259259 size-full" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/laing.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="447" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/laing.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/laing-300x168.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/laing-768x429.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/laing-60x34.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/laing-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>
<h2><strong>Olivia Laing, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374618315" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Silver Book</em></a></strong><strong><br />
FSG, November 11</strong></h2>
<p>Dark and cinematic, surreal and spare, Olivia Laingâ€™s <em>The Silver Book</em> connotes glinting edges, rolls of film stuttering and starting, and performance, constant performance. The book seethes with a faint promise of violence, but we donâ€™t know where it will come from, who it is that holds the potential for cruelty. A Ripley-esque character named Nicholas is the bookâ€™s center; heâ€™s running from a secret past, he will be anyone to anybody, and when he meets Dani, an artist working in Italian cinema, the character is just right. He becomes Daniâ€™s assistant, his lover, his everything. Nicholas was never meant to find himself in this world, but find himself he does, and he sets into motion a conclusion that can never be undone.</p>
<p>The bookâ€™s background is Italy in the 1970s, an era of political upheaval, though the reader only gets glimpses of it. Sometimes itâ€™s easy to forget the specific and transformative time the book is set in, since the reader is plunged so fully into the world of cinema: <em>The Silver Book</em> is mainly about the silver screen, Fellini and Pasolini and the creative, outlandish masterpieces that were being created during the time of tension and tumult. Somehow both spare and ornate, immersive and voyeuristic, <em>The Silver Book</em> has a pull that canâ€™t be denied. <em>â€“JH</em></p>
<p><a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593983751" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259260" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/15-novels-you-need-to-read-this-fall/anti/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/anti.jpg" data-orig-size="800,447" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="anti" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/anti-300x168.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/anti.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-259260" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/anti.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="447" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/anti.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/anti-300x168.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/anti-768x429.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/anti-60x34.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/anti-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></p>
<h2><strong>QNTM, </strong><a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593983751" class="external" target="_blank"><strong><em>There is No Antimemetics Division</em></strong></a><br />
<strong>Ballantine, November 11</strong></h2>
<p>Weâ€™re so familiar with memes and their spread, the way that images or quotes or moments worm into our brainsâ€¦ but what about an anti-meme? Something that erases any evidence of itself? What if an X-Files-style (or Delta Green, or SCP, or so on) organization was dedicated to defending humanity against such an inconceivable threat? And what if that fight didnâ€™t go terribly well? Welcome to the Antimemetics Division; no, it isnâ€™t your first day.</p>
<p>The original version of QNTMâ€™s novel (itself a stitch-up of posts from the <a href="https://scp-wiki.wikidot.com/" class="external" target="_blank">SCP wiki</a>) pleasantly bent my brain with its propulsive prose and high-flying science fiction concept â€” but this version, brought to mass market for the first time, has been thoroughly revised to both make it accessible to uninitiated readers and to make the plot really sing. And boy howdy, does it ever: this reads at the pace of technothrillers by Crichton or Preston &amp; Child, but it is unafraid to force the reader to really work their gray matter in grappling with an idea that by definition cannot be perceived. Absolutely spectacular stuff, for sci-fi fans and those looking for thrills of any stripe. <em>â€“DB</em></p>
<h2><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781681379579" class="external" target="_blank"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="259261" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/15-novels-you-need-to-read-this-fall/thelord/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/thelord.jpg" data-orig-size="800,447" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="thelord" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/thelord-300x168.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/thelord.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-259261" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/thelord.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="447" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/thelord.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/thelord-300x168.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/thelord-768x429.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/thelord-60x34.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/thelord-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></a></h2>
<h2><strong>Soraya Antonius, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781681379579" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Lord</a><br />
</em>NYRB Classics, November 25Â </strong></h2>
<p><em>The Lord </em>is a sharp portrait of pre-Nakba Palestine and its British colonizers, a timely reissue about colonized people and their imperial overseers, unable to see the shape of the world around them. <em>The Lord</em> is beautifully written, with a sympathetic attention to character and culture from Antonius, the daughter of a Mandatory Palestine socialite and an author and civil servant.</p>
<p>The book is narrated by a young journalist, interviewing an elderly woman about her life as a missionary teacher in 1930s Jaffa. She lived surrounded by colonial administrators and as her Palestinian students and their families. One of these students grows up to become a traveling magician, and as his act becomes increasingly uncanny (he turns brandy into juice) and then political (a Homburg hat becomes a keffiya), it gets the attention of colonial authorities. His character is the most interesting, a revolutionary who can only be understood as a cheap trickster. His first â€œmiracleâ€ is doing too well on a placement exam: how could he have done it without divine intervene? The British are baffled.</p>
<p>A historical awareness always lurks just out of view: Sykes, Picot, and Balfour are casually referenced, as is Zionist violence and promises made by the British Empire. There are also echoes in the crumbled crusader castles, spots for picnic excursions and parallels for the barbed wired rolling out across the colony. We know where this is headed, and so does our narrator, but the British charactersâ€™ breezy confidence and deep denial keeps them rooted in well-mannered contempt. As the book progresses, the history becomes harder to ignore and harder to justify away. The strikes and eventual armed revolution in the late â€™30s ramp up, with the colonial administrators only ever considering them â€œevents,â€ disconnected and lacking any throughline in ideology or history.</p>
<p>Any sympathy we might have had starts to curdle as the British characters quickly revert to casual, practiced cruelty. The school teacher did seem to care for her pupils and their families, and to love the country and culture she has adopted. But the piece she is missing and the unbroken tether to the metropole ultimately hobbles her.</p>
<p>The relevance of <em>The Lord</em> is impossible to ignore, especially in the character of a British journalist, who is extremely detached and mercenary. He finds that his dispatches arenâ€™t moving copies like they once were: â€œâ€¦the papers had found other subjects, Palestine not enjoying the capacity to increase sales, and things went on as before, except in the destroyed homes.&#8221; <em>â€“JF</em></p>
<p><strong>Plus just as many fall novels we haven&#8217;t read yet, but that we&#8217;re particularly anticipating:</strong></p>
<p>Sarah Moss, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374609016" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Ripeness</em></a> (FSG, September 9)<br />
Natsuo Kirino, tr. Lisa Hofmann-Kuroda, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780307267580" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Swallows</em></a> (Knopf, September 9)<br />
Angela Flournoy,Â <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063318779" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Wilderness</em></a> (Mariner, September 16)<br />
Kiran Desai, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780307700155" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Loneliness of Sonia and Sunny</a></em> (Hogarth, September 23)<br />
Chris Kraus, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668098684" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Four Spent the Day Together</em></a> (Scribner, October 7)<br />
Megha Majumdar,Â <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593804889" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>A Guardian and a Thief</em></a> (Knopf, October 14)<br />
Ken Liu, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668083178" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>All That We See or Seem</em></a> (Saga Press, October 14)<br />
Adam Johnson, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374619572" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Wayfinder</em></a> (MCD, October 14)<br />
Quan Barry, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780802165350" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Unveiling</em></a> (Grove, October 14)<br />
Claire-Louise Bennett, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9798217046645" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Big Kiss, Bye-Bye</em></a> (Riverhead, October 21)<br />
Oyinkan Braithwaite, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780385551489" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Cursed Daughters</em></a> (Doubleday, November 4)<br />
Bryan Washington, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374609078" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Palaver</em></a> (FSG, November 4)<br />
Quiara AlegrÃ­a Hudes, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593732335" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The White Hot</a></em> (One World, November 11)<br />
Olga Tokarczuk, tr. Antonia Lloyd-Jones,<em> <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593716403" target="_blank" rel="noopener">House of Day, House of Night</a></em> (Riverhead, December 2)<br />
Lauren Rothery, <em><a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063443327" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Television</a></em> (Ecco, December 2)</p>
										
																				
																		
										<div class="post_wrapper author">
											<div id="about_the_author">
												<div class="gravatar"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/emily-temple/"><img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Emily-Temple_select_9612_NS1sm-100x100.jpg" width="100" height="100" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Emily-Temple_select_9612_NS1sm-300x300.jpg 2x" alt="Emily Temple" class="avatar avatar-100 wp-user-avatar wp-user-avatar-100 alignnone photo" /></a></div>
												<div class="description author withsidebar">
													<h6><a href="https://lithub.com/author/emily-temple/">Emily Temple</a></h6>
													Emily Temple is the managing editor at Lit Hub. Her first novel, <em>The Lightness</em>, was published by William Morrow/HarperCollins in June 2020. <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/317/9780062905338" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="external" target="_blank">You can buy it here.</a>																										<div class="website">
